y between the major religions based on dogma and doctrine. &#10;And what about people who profess no religion or profess atheism? Are they entitled to representation in the schools? I would say yes. &#10;If religion is not allowed in the public schools, then some students may leave the public schools for the religion-based schools. If that happens, HOW does that serve to foster understanding, respect and compassion between the diverse peoples of our Canadian society? &#10;Thanks. Perplexed."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="786" language="en" documentId="1473" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Dan1234" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1473" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="254"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="255" end="362"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="363" end="498"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="499" end="767"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="768" end="786"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>